Elite birds, which can fly up to 90 mph, are much sought after, with racing pigeons from a coveted European lineage costing $4,000.
Pigeon racing, a sport on the decline in the United States and Europe, where it was developed, is taking off in Iraq.
After nearly 20 years of conflict in the country, the rising popularity of pigeon racing is a signal that “our people want to practice peace,” said Kamil Khinyab, the 52-year-old undisputed godfather of pigeon racing in Iraq.
Breeders vs. banditsJust as pigeon racing has exploded in popularity, so too has the practice of kidnapping prize birds for ransom.
Pigeon owners spend the six months ahead of the racing season chirping about how they are the best.